    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                <date>June 8th/56</date>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I intended answering your<lb/> long and interesting letter,
                yesterday, but<lb/> as I had exhausted all my stock of<lb/> news to <hi
                    rend="underline"><persName>Stella</persName></hi>, I felt myself unable to<lb/>
                write one worthy of my friend “<hi rend="underline">Bene</hi>”—<lb/> and as mother
                intends favoring you I<lb/> believe with a few lines she wished me<lb/> to write
                yesterday fearing you might have<lb/> left <placeName>Boston</placeName> ere my
                letter would have<lb/> reached its destination, but I flattered<lb/> myself by
                thinking you would not have<lb/> until you had heard from me, me-<lb/>-thinks I hear
                you say how <add>?</add>— “very<lb/> significantly, which would not doubt<lb/> mean
                if translated in plain english<lb/> “What presumption”! N ' importe ce m'est<lb/>
                egale— Who would have supposed<lb/> the <persName>Reverend Isaac Leeser</persName>
                should</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>ever have become a “meddler”, poor<lb/>
                <persName>Mrs Cohen</persName>, her ears must have smarted<lb/> well, whilst you
                were writing, you<lb/> draw so good a picture of the good<lb/> “hold Henglish” lady
                and family<lb/> that you very nearly made me en-<lb/>-vious of not being in your
                place to<lb/> have enjoyed not only their acquaintance<lb/> but their “toute
                ensemble”, Did you<lb/> see <persName>Mrs Joseph</persName> in <placeName>New
                    York</placeName>? I suppose<lb/> not, as you would not have lost so<lb/> good an
                opportunity in lengthening<lb/> your letter. We expect <persName>Uncle
                    Gershom</persName><lb/> on <date>Sunday</date> to spend a day or two with<lb/>
                us as I do not think he will like<lb/> leaving his family for a longer time<lb/>
                just before he goes to <placeName>Europe</placeName>.</p>
            <p>The two <persName>Mr Moses</persName> are in town, <persName>Fred</persName><lb/> and
                    <persName>Brandon</persName>, one from <placeName>California</placeName><lb/>
                the other from <placeName>China</placeName>, they have been<lb/> here for a week,
                they say they admire<lb/>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> exceedingly, best entre</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>nous—I think it is not <hi rend="underline">the city</hi><lb/> that excites their
                admiration as they<lb/> have seen nothing of it with the ex-<lb/>-ception of
                        <placeName><hi rend="underline">Chestnut</hi> St</placeName>, but a<lb/>
                couple of <hi rend="underline">our</hi> fair sex, who they are<lb/> I leave to your
                fertile imagination—<lb/> We have had quite an excitement<lb/> lately that is within
                the last few<lb/> days, about the election of <persName>Mayor<lb/> Judge
                    Conrad</persName> the Whig, and <persName>Mr Vaux</persName><lb/> the
                Democractic Candidate, the Whigs<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">as a matter of course</hi>, gained, Father<lb/> for the <hi
                    rend="underline">first time</hi> I believe voted<lb/> for a democrat, but
                    <persName>Mr Vaux</persName> being<lb/> a personal friend of his, could not
                do<lb/> less. <persName>Uncle Theodore</persName> came on<lb/> last
                    <date>Sunday</date> night and stayed till<lb/>
                <date>Tuesday</date> afternoon, he merely came<lb/> on with
                    <persName>Eugene</persName> to see Grandma<lb/> who is improving slowly. Have
                you<lb/> seen <persName>Mr M. Abecassis</persName> who I hear<lb/> is in
                    <placeName>Boston</placeName> studying law? <hi rend="underline">Your
                    friend</hi></p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p><persName>Fanny Levy</persName> took tea with us <date>Tuesday</date><lb/> evening,
                but as I had an engagement<lb/> to spend the evening out, she did not enjoy my
                society if you go<lb/> to <placeName>Niagra</placeName> I trust you will write
                me<lb/> a faithful description of it, and<lb/> ditto for
                    <placeName>Canada</placeName>—, but “bevare of the<lb/> vomen”, the Canadians in
                particular<lb/> as you know what a fine specimen<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">we once had</hi> in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>,
                chaque<lb/> à son gaut, what pleases one may not<lb/> suit another. There I am half
                way<lb/> down the page and I promised to leave<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">some</hi> space for mother, and I know<lb/> you would not like
                me to break my<lb/> word so good bye, trusting this will meet<lb/> you in health I
                remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">Selena</persName>
            </p>
            <p>As Ma had not an opportunity to add<lb/> in this i would not detain my letter<lb/> as
                    <hi rend="underline">I know</hi> you are all anxiety to<lb/> get, she wishes to
                be kindly remembered<lb/> and <add>?</add> sends her <hi rend="underline">fond</hi>
                love—</p>
            <p rend="letter continues upside down in top margin of page 1">I was quite puzzled about
                directing this<lb/>
                <sic>wether</sic> it should be Reverend or Mr<lb/> let me know which you are in the
                habit of<lb/> receiving</p>
        </body>
